message: Undid revision 1092133677 by [[Special:Contributions/MrOllie|MrOllie]] ([[User talk:MrOllie|talk]]) Reverted biased POV about NPs not being prepared to treat "complex" conditions. 34.2 million Americans have diabetes (https://www.cdc.gov/diabetes/pdfs/data/statistics) a highly complex condition that NPs are prepared to treat. Removed incorrect reference of 100% acceptance in some Masters of Nursing programs with the inference that all of these programs are nurse practitioner programs.
Updated the number of full practice authority states under the Scope of Practice section

Removed "Other nurse practitioner programs have 100% acceptance rates.[13]" as the link https://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/the-short-list-grad-school/articles/nursing-masters-programs-with-the-highest-acceptance-rates is not referencing NP programs but acceptance rates of Masters programs. All Masters programs does not mean that they are nurse practitioner programs.

Under Quality of Care, Removed "...with virtually all of the studies sponsored by nursing organizations." Inherently false that "virtually all of the studies..." were :"sponsored" by nursing organizations. Where is proof of this? What does "sponsored" even mean?
added 26 full practice authority states and reference
Undid revision 1091744088 by [[Special:Contributions/MrOllie|MrOllie]] ([[User talk:MrOllie|talk]]) There is no context and it is NOT a POV, it is biased and unsubstantiated. Please stop

removed part of the sentence "but does not provide the depth of expertise needed to recognize more complex conditions" as this is blatantly false about NPs being able to "recognize" more complex conditions. Its biased and untrue.

/* Quality of care */ the study referenced makes no mention of utilization of nurse practitioners "under physican supervision" increasing access to primary care. In fact, it is quite the opposite. Simply read the study.
/* Quality of care */ "training more physicians" will not increase result in an increase in primary care access. This is opinion and needs to be omitted.
removed "mid-size" as is ambiguous. Can't define the term "mid" with "mid."
/* Drug Enforcement Administration */ added quoted definition from DEA source
/* United States */Removed repeated use of “some” since there are generally no limitations on diagnosing, prescribing and treatments.

/* Patient outcomes */  removed "...supervised by physicians" not all studies involved physician supervision.

/* Education, accreditation, and certification */ Removed , "...while remaining under [[physician]] supervision" since this is not true. Example, NPs in 26 states have full practice authority with no regulated physician supervision or collaboration.
